data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **three** Thread.Abort patterns that must be replaced:

| Pattern Found | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| **Cancellable work loop** | `ProcessLoop()` while loop | `CancellationToken` checked in loop |
| **ThreadAbortException as control flow** | catch block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| **Thread.ResetAbort to continue** | `ResetAbort()` keeps thread alive for next iteration | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check; new CTS per work item |
| **Blocking call interruption** | `GetNextItem()` "may block"; `Thread.Sleep` grace period | Token-aware blocking; `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne` |

### Why this breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it **does not** abort the thread. Your `Stop()` method will crash, and the `ThreadAbortException` catch block will never execute, meaning `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` never runs on cancellation.

---

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Equivalent of the old ThreadAbortException catch block:
                // clean up partial work, then exit the loop gracefully.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we control whether to continue or break.
                // In the original code ResetAbort kept the thread alive for the
                // next iteration; here the while-condition handles that naturally.
                // If you want to continue processing after rollback (like
                // ResetAbort did), use `continue` instead of `break`.
                break;
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully.
        // Uses Join with a timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort.
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            bool exited = _workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
            if (!exited)
            {
                // Thread did not exit in time. Unlike .NET Framework, you
                // CANNOT force-kill it. Log a warning — see pitfalls below.
                Console.Error.WriteLine(
                    "Warning: worker thread did not exit within timeout.");
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### You must also update `GetNextItem` to accept the token

This is the most commonly missed step. If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue), the cancellation token won't interrupt it unless you wire it through:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, immune to cancellation
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // BlockingCollection.Take()
}

// AFTER — unblocks when token is cancelled
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException
}
```

If `GetNextItem` uses `Thread.Sleep`, `WaitHandle.WaitOne`, or similar:

```csharp
// Replace Thread.Sleep with token-aware wait
// BEFORE:
Thread.Sleep(1000);
// AFTER:
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(1));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls for This Specific Migration

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`GetNextItem()` still blocks forever** | If you don't pass the token into blocking calls, `Cancel()` fires but the thread stays stuck. This is the #1 migration bug — cancellation is cooperative, every blocking call in the chain must accept the token. |
| **Cleanup logic lost** | Your `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` was in a `ThreadAbortException` catch. If you remove that catch without moving the logic, partial work is never rolled back. The migrated code moves it to `catch (OperationCanceledException)`. |
| **`ResetAbort` → continue semantics** | The original `ResetAbort()` let the loop continue to the next iteration. In the migrated code, once `_cts` is cancelled it stays cancelled — you can't "un-cancel" it. If you need per-iteration cancellation (e.g., timeout per item), create a **linked CTS per iteration** (see below). |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` not disposed** | `CTS` is `IDisposable`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. The migrated code implements `IDisposable` to clean it up. |
| **`Thread.Join` replaces `Sleep` + `Abort`** | The original `Sleep(2000)` then `Abort()` is replaced with `Join(2s)`. If the thread doesn't exit, **there is no .NET 8 equivalent of force-kill** — you must ensure the code cooperates. |

### Per-Item Timeout (if ResetAbort meant "retry next item")

If the original intent was to abort a single slow item and continue the loop:

```csharp
while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
{
    // Linked CTS: cancels if either the per-item timeout expires
    // OR the parent stop signal fires
    using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(token);
    itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // per-item timeout

    try
    {
        var item = GetNextItem(token);
        ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Per-item timeout, not a full stop — roll back and continue
        RollbackCurrentTransaction();
        continue;
    }
    finally
    {
        FlushBuffers();
    }
}
```

This uses the `when` filter to distinguish "item timed out" (continue) from "full shutdown" (exit).
